entry.title: [zlib] Reland Enable LIT_MEM code path
entry.content:
Introduced on zlib 1.3.0.1, this will allow a small compression

speed improvement at cost of using a bit more memory.



Observed average gain was 2.6% (SPR) and 2.3% (M1).



It is interesting that it will have a bigger impact on files with

higher entropy like JPG (+5.3%) and pre-compressed (baddata +7%),

probably because those are cases where more literals are produced

by the encoder since it is harder to find matches in LZ77 for such

inputs.

entry.content:
Usually, the FakeServer automatically flushes any pending data to disk

on destruction. However, restarting the app (via

`ensureAppLaunchedWithConfiguration`) doesn't (always?) cleanly shut

it down first, and so FakeServer's destructor doesn't actually get run.



This CL introduces an explicit FlushToDisk method that tests can call

just before restarting the app.

So far, no tests are making use of this - the first test that does is

entry.title: [perf] Make IsFoo() methods virtual in LayoutObject hierarchy.
entry.content:
Previously we had 3 different IsFoo() implementations:

1. The IsOfType() (e.g. IsTableCell()).

2. Specialized bits on LayoutObject, (e.g. IsText()).

3. Virtual methods (e.g. IsBoxModelObject()).



(1) was the primary type - and was done to reduce vtable size in:

https://codereview.chromium.org/613783002



However after that patch landed an optimization (for Chromium) in

clang appeared called "virtual constant propagation". See:

https://lists.llvm.org/pipermail/llvm-dev/2016-January/094600.html

https://llvm.org/doxygen/WholeProgramDevirt_8cpp_source.html#:~:text=14//%20%2D-,Virtual%20constant%20propagation,-%3A%20if%20the%20virtual



The TL;DR of this optimization is if a virtual function always returns

the same value, for some class, that value will be stored in the

vtable and not have to invoke a function call.



For this specific patch this means that we don't need to invoke the

IsOfType() function, and instead the

"virtual bool IsTableCell() const final { return true; }"

should be stored in the vtable instead.



This patch also changes the micro-perf'd IsText & IsBox to just

virtual functions instead.



A similar approach without the binary size increase is:

https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/5118379

(Instead of a IsOfType() have a virtual GetType() , but this is

slightly more fragile to breaking, and marginally more complex).



This performance issue was originally noticed by Lingyun Cai in:

https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/5067069



Overall performance numbers are (roughly):

+1.1% in speedometer3

+0.2% in speedometer2 (probably)

+0.4% in motionmark (maybe)



Binary-Size: Performance gain of ~1% on speedometer3.

entry.title: [Blink] Convert DrawingBuffer to MappableSharedImage
entry.content:
This CL converts DrawingBuffer from using GpuMemoryBuffer to using

MappableSharedImage. The conversion is straightforward:



* Currently DrawingBuffer creates a GMB and then immediately creates

an SI from the GMB's handle.

* We instead create an SI via the CreateSI() path that causes a backing

GMBHandle to be created internally.

* Where the code previously checked for the GMB having been created, we

now track a bool explicitly for whether the MapppableSI was created.

* We remove ColorBuffer's keeping the GMB alive for its lifetime.

ColorBuffer already keeps the SI alive for its lifetime (it's put into

`back_buffer_mailbox`, which is passed to the created ColorBuffer and

on which that ColorBuffer calls DestroySI() at the same time as it

resets() the gmb)

* We remove the check for Platform having a GMBManager from

ShouldUseChromiumImage(). This check only served to ensure that the

code didn't try to create a GMB from a null GMBManager. MappableSI

doesn't use Platform's GMBManager to create GMBs internally. In the

current structure of the code any failure to create MappableSI will

flow down to the non-ShouldUseChromiumImage() case, as the code is

currently doing if there is no GMBManager.
